ce:section.ce:para:
To apply MOX for quantitative determination of Fe3+ in real water sample, a fluorescence titration experiment was performed. As can be seen from Fig. 5a, the fluorescence intensities were weakened gradually with the increase of Fe3+ concentration, showing in quadratic curve. However, a good liner relationship (R
                        =0.9980) can be observed between (F0–F) and [Fe3+]1/2 at Fe3+ concentration from 0.05 to 15μM (Fig. 5b). The detection limit is calculated to be 32nM (3 SD/S), which is much lower than most of the reported in literatures (Table 1
                        ). On the other hand, it must be noted that there exist a large difference between the MOX probe and most of the fluorescent probes reported. The MOX based Fe3+-probe can operate excellently in pure water solution, and most of the fluorescent probes reported previously can only be performed in pure organic [12,34] or the organic solvent modified water solution [19,21–24,29,32,33]. The comparison about the detection limit, linearity range and detection media between the present method and those reported in literature was shown in Table 1.
